101
00:05:45,378 --> 00:05:48,220
It says in the program that I was going to talk about

102
00:05:48,220 --> 00:05:49,480
Georgians and Victorians, but I'll

103
00:05:49,480 --> 00:05:52,463
have to tell you about my heroes, Mary Wollstonecraft

104
00:05:52,463 --> 00:05:53,683
and William Morris another time.

105
00:05:53,683 --> 00:05:54,904
I decided to narrow my focus.

106
00:05:55,885 --> 00:05:58,506
Because I'm very interested in realism in video games.

107
00:05:58,506 --> 00:06:05,050
Now for what I want to talk about today, I don't mean realism in the sense of improved physics or better lighting,

108
00:06:05,050 --> 00:06:07,912
though I am very interested in those things too.

109
00:06:07,912 --> 00:06:12,195
Today I mean realism in the sense of the realist artistic movements,

110
00:06:12,195 --> 00:06:14,556
in painting, literary fiction and film,

111
00:06:14,556 --> 00:06:19,599
which emerged in the middle of the 19th century and which have been present in the arts ever since.

112
00:06:21,198 --> 00:06:25,740
The original goal of realism was to show what life is like for ordinary people

113
00:06:25,740 --> 00:06:29,121
without any kind of romantic idealization or

114
00:06:29,121 --> 00:06:32,243
sentimentality or over-dramatization.

115
00:06:32,243 --> 00:06:35,424
Of course, for hundreds of years, most of the pictures that got painted

116
00:06:35,424 --> 00:06:39,186
were portraits of kings and popes, the ruling classes.

117
00:06:39,186 --> 00:06:41,527
All those paintings were related to their lifestyles.

118
00:06:41,527 --> 00:06:44,809
And when other kinds of people were shown, it was usually through some kind of

119
00:06:44,809 --> 00:06:48,190
ideological lens that really distorted how those people were shown.

120
00:06:48,831 --> 00:06:51,543
Now realism wanted to redress that imbalance.

121
00:06:53,227 --> 00:06:56,850
I think it's fair to say that when games draw narratively from film and literature,

122
00:06:56,850 --> 00:07:00,673
they usually draw from genre film and genre fiction,

123
00:07:00,673 --> 00:07:02,815
mostly science fiction, fantasy, and horror.

124
00:07:02,815 --> 00:07:08,000
Now, I loved genre fiction with a passion as a kid, and I still really love it.

125
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:13,085
In high school, I fell in love with the films of Terry Gilliam and David Cronenberg,

126
00:07:13,085 --> 00:07:15,127
who have mainly made genre movies,

127
00:07:15,127 --> 00:07:18,790
but whose works are transcendent in the way that all great art is.

128
00:07:20,648 --> 00:07:25,311
But as much as I love genre fiction, I think that if you're really paying attention to the world around you,

129
00:07:25,311 --> 00:07:33,036
there comes a point when you realize that real life is even more interesting than these kinds of fantasy worlds.

130
00:07:34,060 --> 00:07:40,182
So later in my teenage years, I started to see films by David Lynch, Mike Lee, Ken Loach, and Nick Roeg.

131
00:07:40,182 --> 00:07:45,144
And by the time I got to college, I'd become a fully-fledged arthouse cinema fan.

132
00:07:45,144 --> 00:07:50,446
I saw a lot of weird, experimental film, a lot of international cinema, and a lot of great drama.

133
00:07:50,446 --> 00:07:55,248
And eventually, I realized that many of the films I liked best, which had the deepest emotion,

134
00:07:55,688 --> 00:08:00,591
and that were most helpful to me in figuring out what life is all about,

135
00:08:00,591 --> 00:08:04,833
were set in the real world and were about the extraordinary situations that we

136
00:08:04,833 --> 00:08:06,414
regularly encounter

137
00:08:06,414 --> 00:08:11,798
in everyday life. Now what do we mean when we talk about realism in cinema?

138
00:08:11,798 --> 00:08:15,760
Well, there are probably lots of ways to trace that history, but here's just one of them.

139
00:08:15,760 --> 00:08:20,203
A good starting point, I think, is Jean Renoir, a French writer and director.

140
00:08:20,203 --> 00:08:23,124
He was the son of the impressionist painter Pierre-Auguste Renoir.

141
00:08:24,877 --> 00:08:28,442
In 1937, Renoir released a film called Grand Illusion.

142
00:08:28,442 --> 00:08:32,528
It's about the relationship between a group of people in a prisoner of war camp during

143
00:08:32,528 --> 00:08:38,056
World War I as they work together on an escape plan across the boundaries of their nationality,

144
00:08:38,056 --> 00:08:40,540
their social class, and ethnicity.

145
00:08:41,988 --> 00:08:45,869
Now Orson Welles cited this as one of his favorite films of all time.

146
00:08:45,869 --> 00:08:50,451
And it has an authenticity and a kind of a generous attitude to its characters

147
00:08:50,451 --> 00:08:53,752
that was pretty rare in film at that time.

148
00:08:53,752 --> 00:08:55,253
Um, and it's an amazing film.

149
00:08:55,253 --> 00:08:57,993
It's one of those films where two hours just flies by like that.

150
00:08:57,993 --> 00:08:59,594
I can't recommend it highly enough.

151
00:09:01,118 --> 00:09:03,519
So jumping forward a decade to the end of World War II,

152
00:09:03,519 --> 00:09:07,960
and the Italian film industry had suddenly been freed from the censorship

153
00:09:07,960 --> 00:09:10,961
imposed on it by Mussolini's fascist government.

154
00:09:10,961 --> 00:09:12,221
Influenced by Jean Renoir,

155
00:09:12,221 --> 00:09:16,483
a group of film critics took advantage of their newfound creative freedom

156
00:09:16,483 --> 00:09:20,324
to kickstart the cinematic movement now known as Neo-Realism.

157
00:09:20,324 --> 00:09:23,405
They began to make films about the lives of regular people,

158
00:09:23,405 --> 00:09:27,206
often using non-actors, and filmed on location against the beautiful

159
00:09:27,206 --> 00:09:30,607
but poverty-stricken background of post-war Italy.

160
00:09:32,097 --> 00:09:36,539
Now one amazing film to come out of this movement is Bicycle Thieves, from 1948.

161
00:09:36,539 --> 00:09:41,140
It's about a father searching Rome for his stolen bicycle,

162
00:09:41,140 --> 00:09:45,682
a bicycle without which he will lose the job that feeds his young family.

163
00:09:45,682 --> 00:09:51,223
A few years later, Italian neorealism lit the fuse for the French New Wave of cinema,

164
00:09:51,223 --> 00:09:55,285
which was also founded by young film critics longing for innovation

165
00:09:55,285 --> 00:09:58,206
and working in collaboration with older French filmmakers

166
00:09:58,206 --> 00:10:01,087
who wanted to bring their experience to do something new.

167
00:10:02,506 --> 00:10:06,893
I'm sure you guys have heard of the French New Wave and its key directors Jean-Luc Godard and FranÃ§ois Truffaut.

168
00:10:06,893 --> 00:10:11,380
My personal favorite film from this time is Truffaut's The 400 Blows.

169
00:10:11,380 --> 00:10:16,929
It's a loosely autobiographical story about a misunderstood kid getting into trouble with the system.

170
00:10:18,534 --> 00:10:23,755
By the way, I think it's really interesting to note that in both of these historically important film movements,

171
00:10:23,755 --> 00:10:28,657
critics that had been writing about film became filmmakers themselves.

172
00:10:28,657 --> 00:10:32,638
And their work caused tremendous change all throughout the world.

173
00:10:32,638 --> 00:10:38,279
So even though the directors of the French New Wave were often reacting against a lot of Hollywood convention,

174
00:10:38,279 --> 00:10:43,400
they ended up being massively influential on the next generation of Hollywood filmmakers,

175
00:10:43,400 --> 00:10:46,241
everyone from Steven Spielberg to Martin Scorsese.

176
00:10:47,795 --> 00:10:53,101
And in just the same way, in games right now, critics and writers like Matty Bryce, Cara

177
00:10:53,101 --> 00:10:56,945
Ellison and Tom Francis are becoming game designers.

178
00:10:56,945 --> 00:11:02,011
And the work that they're making is feeding right back into the mainstream of games in

179
00:11:02,011 --> 00:11:04,493
many positive and very healthy ways.

180
00:11:06,217 --> 00:11:11,778
Anyway, so that's some historical setup for realist film. There are lots more reference points that you guys probably know about,

181
00:11:11,778 --> 00:11:15,800
from the 1960s kitchen sink dramas of the British new wave,

182
00:11:15,800 --> 00:11:18,300
to the gritty realism of the 60s and 70s American filmmaking,

183
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:23,842
and of course there were lots of similar movements in international cinema.

184
00:11:23,842 --> 00:11:27,243
As just one example, the work of Indian directors like Chetan Anand.

185
00:11:28,264 --> 00:11:32,791
But now I want to tell you about a few great recent realist films that have had a big influence on me...

186
00:11:32,791 --> 00:11:36,376
...and that I think might not be very well known in our community of game makers.

187
00:11:38,281 --> 00:11:42,402
In 1999, the Scottish director Lynne Ramsay released this moving film called Rat Catcher.

188
00:11:42,402 --> 00:11:46,104
The movie's innovative cinematography and editing was described as immersive

189
00:11:46,104 --> 00:11:49,345
by some critics, which I think is interesting in relation to games,

190
00:11:49,345 --> 00:11:54,107
and it showed that you can always find new things to do with an artistic form if you

191
00:11:54,107 --> 00:11:58,528
work at it. In games, I think we've barely begun to push cinematography

192
00:11:58,528 --> 00:12:02,510
in the way that this film does, in terms of unconventional framing and

193
00:12:02,510 --> 00:12:04,030
impressionistic use of

194
00:12:04,030 --> 00:12:07,312
light and unconventional editing, stuff like that.

195
00:12:08,468 --> 00:12:13,393
The movie's set in Glasgow in the early 70s, and like several of the films I want to tell you about,

196
00:12:13,393 --> 00:12:16,716
it's about a kid from a challenging background, this boy James.

197
00:12:16,716 --> 00:12:21,861
He's patiently waiting for his family to be relocated to a new public housing project

198
00:12:21,861 --> 00:12:25,385
as he tries to deal with the fallout from something bad that recently happened to him.

199
00:12:27,122 --> 00:12:31,262
Coincidentally, another of the films I want to tell you about is set in Glasgow.

200
00:12:31,262 --> 00:12:37,204
One of two films that I'll tell you about by another British director, Andrea Arnold.

201
00:12:37,204 --> 00:12:41,685
Red Road from 2006 was made in response to a game-like project

202
00:12:41,685 --> 00:12:47,006
where a group of Danish and German film producers challenged three different filmmakers

203
00:12:47,006 --> 00:12:51,667
to use a number of the same predefined characters in three different movies.

204
00:12:52,991 --> 00:12:55,812
Red Road was the first movie to be made in response to this challenge.

205
00:12:55,812 --> 00:13:00,835
It's about a woman who works monitoring police closed-circuit television feeds

206
00:13:00,835 --> 00:13:04,297
from public housing projects, and in doing so she encounters

207
00:13:04,297 --> 00:13:09,119
a man from a very bad part of her past. These issues around voyeurism and

208
00:13:09,119 --> 00:13:11,261
surveillance have been explored a bit by games,

209
00:13:11,261 --> 00:13:15,923
and I think they're an interesting fit for interactivity. Maybe this film shows

210
00:13:15,923 --> 00:13:16,803
us some new

211
00:13:16,803 --> 00:13:17,964
creative ways forward.

212
00:13:19,141 --> 00:13:21,863
The main character in this film, by the way, you might recognize.

213
00:13:21,863 --> 00:13:24,446
She's played by the brilliant Kate Dickey,

214
00:13:24,446 --> 00:13:27,188
who also plays Lyssa Arryn in Game of Thrones.

215
00:13:27,188 --> 00:13:30,371
Andrea Arnold's next film, Fish Tank,

216
00:13:30,371 --> 00:13:35,675
is one of those rare films that manages to be both funny and heart-rending.

217
00:13:35,675 --> 00:13:40,559
It's about an isolated teenage girl whose only real passion is hip-hop dance,

218
00:13:40,559 --> 00:13:44,263
as she struggles to find her way through life and to try and connect with the world.

219
00:13:45,078 --> 00:13:47,639
It's got Michael Fassbender in it, I'm sure you know.

220
00:13:47,639 --> 00:13:51,301
He's done a lot of amazing work, including his turn as Archie Hickox in

221
00:13:51,301 --> 00:13:52,882
Inglourious Bastards,

222
00:13:52,882 --> 00:13:58,625
and first-time actor Katie Jarvis is really brilliant in the main role.

223
00:13:58,625 --> 00:14:02,087
Another British realist film that I think some of you might have seen is

224
00:14:02,087 --> 00:14:03,948
Weekend, directed by Andrew Hay.

225
00:14:03,948 --> 00:14:06,530
This is a very powerful and moving film

226
00:14:06,530 --> 00:14:09,651
about two men who hook up on a Friday night, beginning what

227
00:14:09,651 --> 00:14:12,013
initially just seems like a casual sexual encounter.

228
00:14:13,124 --> 00:14:16,146
But as the relationship unfolds over the course of the weekend,

229
00:14:16,146 --> 00:14:20,889
the film manages to explore big issues around intimacy and commitment,

230
00:14:20,889 --> 00:14:25,152
as well as leading a political discussion about what life is like for gay people

231
00:14:25,152 --> 00:14:26,193
in contemporary society.

232
00:14:27,764 --> 00:14:31,749
And like a number of other realist films, this movie has great

233
