00:23:23,602 --> 00:23:26,503
Like, there's nothing about that and what we do

374
00:23:26,503 --> 00:23:30,185
that's worth hurting ourselves, hurting one another,

375
00:23:30,185 --> 00:23:31,586
or the ones that we love.

376
00:23:31,586 --> 00:23:35,788
So we should definitely incorporate more musical numbers

377
00:23:35,788 --> 00:23:37,189
into our data rate process as well.

378
00:23:39,293 --> 00:23:42,354
So second is to be creative, you have to take risks.

379
00:23:42,354 --> 00:23:43,834
And in order to take risks, you have

380
00:23:43,834 --> 00:23:44,974
to feel that you're in an environment which

381
00:23:44,974 --> 00:23:46,395
is safe to fail.

382
00:23:46,395 --> 00:23:49,576
This was really a motto of Henson's

383
00:23:49,576 --> 00:23:53,157
and certainly came out through many of the trials

384
00:23:53,157 --> 00:23:54,977
and tribulations that the Muppets faced

385
00:23:54,977 --> 00:23:57,058
in putting on a show every night.

386
00:23:57,893 --> 00:24:11,117
It's also one of the biggest mistakes I see happening in our industry, which somehow I feel has perpetuated this notion that everyone thrives better in a really competitive, hostile environment in which you're asked to prove yourself every day.

387
00:24:11,117 --> 00:24:20,899
And I think it's why we drive many brilliant, creative people away from making games professionally, and especially in the commercial marketplace.

388
00:24:20,899 --> 00:24:25,600
So this statement right here, it's the key to innovation. It's everything.

389
00:24:26,954 --> 00:24:29,135
So now I'm not saying that you have to create an environment

390
00:24:29,135 --> 00:24:33,298
in which everyone is pampered and everyone wins all the time.

391
00:24:33,298 --> 00:24:35,740
I think you want to put together the right team for your game

392
00:24:35,740 --> 00:24:36,920
from the start.

393
00:24:36,920 --> 00:24:39,522
But once I've decided to work with someone,

394
00:24:39,522 --> 00:24:42,444
I give them enough rope to hang themselves with.

395
00:24:42,444 --> 00:24:45,265
Because that's when I think creative people

396
00:24:45,265 --> 00:24:46,926
produce their best work.

397
00:24:47,347 --> 00:24:50,088
You want a team of people that push and challenge one another

398
00:24:50,088 --> 00:24:52,308
because they come from different backgrounds,

399
00:24:52,308 --> 00:24:54,889
they're bringing different ideas to the table,

400
00:24:54,889 --> 00:24:56,730
and all of those ideas can be heard.

401
00:24:56,730 --> 00:24:59,971
That's how you get the best ideas,

402
00:24:59,971 --> 00:25:02,932
not by pitting a homogenous group of people

403
00:25:02,932 --> 00:25:03,733
against one another.

404
00:25:06,753 --> 00:25:10,894
And this point might seem a bit dodgy based

405
00:25:10,894 --> 00:25:12,135
on what I just said.

406
00:25:12,135 --> 00:25:14,076
But going back to my second point,

407
00:25:14,076 --> 00:25:17,577
the people you work with, you might as well be dating,

