00:29:29,501 --> 00:29:30,562
It was not my basement.

477
00:29:30,562 --> 00:29:31,763
All right, cool.

478
00:29:31,763 --> 00:29:33,064
Take it away, Ben.

479
00:29:33,064 --> 00:29:35,106
All right, hey.

480
00:29:35,106 --> 00:29:36,267
I wanted to talk to you.

481
00:29:36,267 --> 00:29:40,410
OK, so I first wanted to say that I think film definitely

482
00:29:40,410 --> 00:29:43,453
influences my work a lot, but I would say music probably does

483
00:29:43,453 --> 00:29:43,853
more.

484
00:29:44,724 --> 00:29:48,585
My background is, a lot of it is from music and electronic music.

485
00:29:48,585 --> 00:29:51,545
And so I want to talk about Brian Eno, who

486
00:29:51,545 --> 00:29:55,706
is one of the most influential electronic musicians,

487
00:29:55,706 --> 00:29:59,487
or like, did whatever, like synthesizer

488
00:29:59,487 --> 00:30:00,107
and electronic music.

489
00:30:00,107 --> 00:30:04,028
So he's also the most quotable guy on the planet.

490
00:30:04,028 --> 00:30:05,488
So I'm going to show you quotes.

491
00:30:05,488 --> 00:30:09,229
And I'm going to, if you talk to me afterwards,

492
00:30:09,229 --> 00:30:11,670
I'll give you some resources for awesome stuff, like interviews

493
00:30:11,670 --> 00:30:12,310
and stuff that he says.

494
00:30:12,916 --> 00:30:16,117
So kind of the main idea I wanted to start with

495
00:30:16,117 --> 00:30:18,458
was this one quote, which says, the idea

496
00:30:18,458 --> 00:30:20,779
is to produce things that are strange and mysterious to you

497
00:30:20,779 --> 00:30:22,160
as the first music you ever heard.

498
00:30:22,160 --> 00:30:26,261
And to me, that's kind of a goal with a lot of my work,

499
00:30:26,261 --> 00:30:30,143
is to reproduce those kind of magical experiences

500
00:30:30,143 --> 00:30:32,644
that you didn't quite understand at first.

501
00:30:32,644 --> 00:30:34,545
So I'm going to try to tie that back up.

502
00:30:36,119 --> 00:30:38,441
So if you're not familiar with Brian Eno's work,

503
00:30:38,441 --> 00:30:41,703
he's known for working with David Bowie and Devo

504
00:30:41,703 --> 00:30:42,684
in Talking Heads.

505
00:30:42,684 --> 00:30:47,827
He also produced Coldplay and U2 for More Contemporary.

506
00:30:47,827 --> 00:30:49,648
He popularized the term ambient music,

507
00:30:49,648 --> 00:30:53,631
and he also popularized the term generative music

508
00:30:53,631 --> 00:30:56,773
with his album Discrete Music that I'm going to talk about

509
00:30:56,773 --> 00:30:57,433
a little bit later.

510
00:30:58,108 --> 00:31:01,531
which was kind of both ambient and generative.

511
00:31:01,531 --> 00:31:05,854
He's also known for some video and installation art.

512
00:31:05,854 --> 00:31:09,777
77 Million Paintings was one of his generative works

513
00:31:09,777 --> 00:31:12,519
that is kind of like generative paintings set

514
00:31:12,519 --> 00:31:13,340
to generative music.

515
00:31:13,340 --> 00:31:17,903
And the idea is that there's 77 million possible combinations.

516
00:31:17,903 --> 00:31:20,605
And it would take you like 450 years of watching it

517
00:31:20,605 --> 00:31:21,626
to see all of them.

518
00:31:23,652 --> 00:31:26,492
OK, so first I wanted to talk about how I was introduced

519
00:31:26,492 --> 00:31:27,153
to Brian Eno.

520
00:31:27,153 --> 00:31:31,554
So I'll play you the first piece that I ever heard,

521
00:31:31,554 --> 00:31:35,195
and it was pretty influential to me.

522
00:31:35,195 --> 00:31:37,735
And so I want to make sure sound's on.

523
00:31:37,735 --> 00:31:42,236
All right, and so you might have heard this song too.

524
00:31:42,236 --> 00:31:42,657
So I'll play it.

525
00:31:49,610 --> 00:31:51,652
So it's six seconds long.

526
00:31:51,652 --> 00:31:54,575
If you don't know where it's from,

527
00:31:54,575 --> 00:31:56,737
it's the Windows 95 startup sound.

528
00:31:56,737 --> 00:32:04,445
So Microsoft commissioned him to produce a piece of music

529
00:32:04,445 --> 00:32:09,190
that was kind of like, they used every possible adjective

530
00:32:09,190 --> 00:32:10,612
to describe this piece of music.

531
00:32:11,041 --> 00:32:14,182
futuristic and nostalgic and sentimental.

532
00:32:14,182 --> 00:32:18,564
And so he wasn't a big fan of Microsoft,

533
00:32:18,564 --> 00:32:20,365
but he did think the challenge of making

534
00:32:20,365 --> 00:32:24,427
a three-second piece of music was incredible and kind of funny.

535
00:32:24,427 --> 00:32:27,688
So I think that's a good encapsulation

536
00:32:27,688 --> 00:32:29,149
of a lot of the stuff he talks about.

537
00:32:29,988 --> 00:32:35,295
So what's important to Brian Eno is theory over practice.

538
00:32:35,295 --> 00:32:38,459
And it's something that I kind of subscribe to, too.

539
00:32:38,459 --> 00:32:40,861
Where there is certainly a craft to music,

540
00:32:40,861 --> 00:32:42,263
and there's a craft to developing games.

541
00:32:42,976 --> 00:32:44,257
and any form of art.

542
00:32:44,257 --> 00:32:46,999
But in terms of being an artist, I

543
00:32:46,999 --> 00:32:50,261
think process is the most important thing to me.

544
00:32:50,261 --> 00:32:54,684
So Brian Eno, all of his work is informed

545
00:32:54,684 --> 00:32:58,466
by a specific theory or process that he wants to explore.

546
00:32:58,466 --> 00:33:02,148
And so he says, even though the viewer or the listener

547
00:33:02,148 --> 00:33:03,169
or the player might not.

548
00:33:03,901 --> 00:33:07,383
understand or be aware of the theory behind what they're

549
00:33:07,383 --> 00:33:08,444
experiencing.

550
00:33:08,444 --> 00:33:11,226
It's the fact that it informed it meant that it could create

551
00:33:11,226 --> 00:33:14,649
an experience that they might not have otherwise seen.

552
00:33:14,649 --> 00:33:18,772
So the next thing I want to talk about is constraint.

553
00:33:18,772 --> 00:33:20,693
So he's got this other great quote.

554
00:33:20,693 --> 00:33:23,735
There's a reason that guitar players invariably produce

555
00:33:23,735 --> 00:33:25,377
more interesting music than synth players.

556
00:33:25,737 --> 00:33:27,859
And it's that you can go through the options on a guitar

557
00:33:27,859 --> 00:33:28,579
in a minute.

558
00:33:28,579 --> 00:33:31,021
After that, you have to make aesthetic and stylistic

559
00:33:31,021 --> 00:33:31,901
decisions.

560
00:33:31,901 --> 00:33:36,325
And so I think this applies to digital artists,

561
00:33:36,325 --> 00:33:39,147
because when the synthesizer came out.

562
00:33:40,100 --> 00:33:44,562
It's got all these knobs and you kind of have an infinite amount of options.

563
00:33:44,562 --> 00:33:49,005
And that often makes it way more difficult for you to produce anything interesting.

564
00:33:49,005 --> 00:33:52,787
And so, yeah, this quote kind of ties it up nicely where he says,

565
00:33:52,787 --> 00:33:56,168
what you need are fewer possibilities that are more interesting.

566
00:33:56,168 --> 00:34:00,871
And so, what he wants to create are constraints that allow you

567
00:34:00,871 --> 00:34:07,294
to be making aesthetic and stylistic decisions rather than technical decisions.

568
00:34:08,565 --> 00:34:10,946
So I want to talk about one of his most famous works,

569
00:34:10,946 --> 00:34:11,607
Discrete Music.

570
00:34:11,607 --> 00:34:14,449
It's a piece of ambient music, and it's

571
00:34:14,449 --> 00:34:16,990
a piece of generative music.

572
00:34:16,990 --> 00:34:18,892
And I'll describe what ambient music means.

573
00:34:18,892 --> 00:34:20,393
You probably are familiar with it now.

574
00:34:20,393 --> 00:34:23,935
But the story behind the album is that Brian Eno

575
00:34:23,935 --> 00:34:25,376
got into a car crash.

576
00:34:25,376 --> 00:34:26,276
And he was.

577
00:34:26,834 --> 00:34:30,196
recovering in bed, and he wanted to listen to music.

578
00:34:30,196 --> 00:34:34,419
And so he had a record of classical harp music.

579
00:34:34,419 --> 00:34:37,101
And so he got up, and he mustered all his strength

580
00:34:37,101 --> 00:34:38,862
to put the record on.

581
00:34:38,862 --> 00:34:42,984
And he moved the needle on, and he went back and laid in bed.

582
00:34:42,984 --> 00:34:45,046
And then couldn't really hear the music.

583
00:34:45,046 --> 00:34:46,647
And it turns out the volume was down.

584
00:34:47,219 --> 00:34:49,981
to an almost imperceptible level,

585
00:34:49,981 --> 00:34:53,663
but he felt too weak to go and turn the volume up.

586
00:34:53,663 --> 00:34:56,665
So he decided to listen to the music

587
00:34:56,665 --> 00:34:57,985
at this almost imperceptible volume.

588
00:34:57,985 --> 00:35:00,607
And so it kind of came in and out of consciousness.

589
00:35:00,607 --> 00:35:03,128
And that was, this is his quote,

590
00:35:03,128 --> 00:35:07,051
this presented what was for me a new way of hearing music

591
00:35:07,051 --> 00:35:08,912
as part of the ambience of the environment,

592
00:35:08,912 --> 00:35:10,713
just as the color of the light and the sound of the rain

593
00:35:10,713 --> 00:35:13,795
were parts of that ambience.

594
00:35:19,211 --> 00:35:25,135
So ambient music is about the gray area between attention

595
00:35:25,135 --> 00:35:26,996
and background.

596
00:35:26,996 --> 00:35:31,639
And so that's an area I really enjoy exploring in my work,

597
00:35:31,639 --> 00:35:35,502
where instead of upfront systems and game mechanics,

598
00:35:35,502 --> 00:35:39,265
I think creating environments and worlds that

599
00:35:39,265 --> 00:35:41,626
dance between things that are worthy of attention,

600
00:35:41,626 --> 00:35:45,189
things that are the background, are the most interesting places

601
00:35:45,189 --> 00:35:45,689
to explore.

602
00:35:46,734 --> 00:35:48,995
And then the other part of discrete music

603
00:35:48,995 --> 00:35:49,975
is that it's generative.

604
00:35:49,975 --> 00:35:55,997
And what that means is that the piece is started with a seed,

605
00:35:55,997 --> 00:35:59,958
and then some other process that is set up by the artist

606
00:35:59,958 --> 00:36:01,319
finishes the work for you.

607
00:36:01,319 --> 00:36:03,319
And so you don't necessarily have control

608
00:36:03,319 --> 00:36:04,560
over the final product.

609
00:36:04,560 --> 00:36:05,640
You just started it.

610
00:36:05,640 --> 00:36:08,701
And that's kind of video games.

611
00:36:10,213 --> 00:36:13,334
software does this really well, but it kind of was being

612
00:36:13,334 --> 00:36:16,415
explored for generations and generations before that in

613
00:36:16,415 --> 00:36:17,676
other forms of art.

614
00:36:17,676 --> 00:36:22,377
And so on the back of Discrete Music, he generously

615
00:36:22,377 --> 00:36:26,098
reproduced the diagram of how the work was produced.

616
00:36:26,098 --> 00:36:28,539
It's a 30-minute piece.

617
00:36:28,539 --> 00:36:31,500
And the idea is that it starts on a synthesizer and then goes

618
00:36:31,500 --> 00:36:32,060
into a tape recorder.

619
00:36:32,060 --> 00:36:36,581
And then that tape goes to a tape player.

620
00:36:37,150 --> 00:36:39,251
which goes back into the tape recorder,

621
00:36:39,251 --> 00:36:41,572
and then gets recorded.

622
00:36:41,572 --> 00:36:45,513
And so the idea is he starts with a synth line,

623
00:36:45,513 --> 00:36:48,755
and there's kind of like a melodic idea behind it.

624
00:36:48,755 --> 00:36:50,835
And then it feeds back onto itself

625
00:36:50,835 --> 00:36:52,316
at a different point in time.

626
00:36:52,316 --> 00:36:57,338
And he can stretch the delay and make it shorter or longer

627
00:36:57,338 --> 00:37:00,259
to kind of create new results that were unexpected.

628
00:37:00,259 --> 00:37:01,659
And that was.

629
00:37:02,745 --> 00:37:07,187
and amazing at the time, and the technology allowed that.

630
00:37:07,187 --> 00:37:10,229
But it's something that we can do now,

631
00:37:10,229 --> 00:37:14,751
where we can plant the seeds and have an intention behind it.

632
00:37:14,751 --> 00:37:20,554
But I think letting the viewer take hold of what that means

633
00:37:20,554 --> 00:37:24,096
and how the system affected it is really

634
00:37:24,096 --> 00:37:25,817
important to digital works.

635
00:37:25,817 --> 00:37:27,777
So I want to talk a little bit about.

636
00:37:29,210 --> 00:37:31,711
This game is in Finish Swan.

637
00:37:31,711 --> 00:37:35,154
If you don't know it, it starts and it's all white,

638
00:37:35,154 --> 00:37:40,197
and you throw black paint to reveal the environment.

639
00:37:40,197 --> 00:37:44,260
And this was, for me, an ambient game in a lot of ways.

640
00:37:44,260 --> 00:37:46,762
So there's not much gameplay other than getting

641
00:37:46,762 --> 00:37:48,263
from point A to point B.

642
00:37:48,263 --> 00:37:53,106
And a lot of the level design.

643
00:37:53,763 --> 00:37:56,045
Like, the focus for me on the level design

644
00:37:56,045 --> 00:37:57,907
were things that were ambient.

645
00:37:57,907 --> 00:38:00,849
So because there is no gameplay per se,

646
00:38:00,849 --> 00:38:05,294
interacting with other agents in the system,

647
00:38:05,294 --> 00:38:08,877
I wanted all the details and objects and backgrounds

648
00:38:08,877 --> 00:38:11,700
to take the place of that and kind of be

649
00:38:11,700 --> 00:38:14,883
able to go in and out of your consciousness

650
00:38:14,883 --> 00:38:15,623
and your attention.

651
00:38:18,292 --> 00:38:22,580
So this is a deck of cards called Oblique Strategies.

652
00:38:22,580 --> 00:38:26,589
This has more to do with his idea of constraint,

653
00:38:26,589 --> 00:38:28,412
and I think has helped inform my process a lot.

654
00:38:30,951 --> 00:38:32,613
Oblique strategies is a deck of cards

655
00:38:32,613 --> 00:38:36,357
that's a bunch of challenges or dilemmas

656
00:38:36,357 --> 00:38:38,178
to help you get over blocks in your work.

657
00:38:38,178 --> 00:38:41,242
These are a couple of examples, like honor thy error

658
00:38:41,242 --> 00:38:42,083
as a hidden intention.

659
00:38:42,083 --> 00:38:45,306
An idea is when you're blocked, you can take the card out.

660
00:38:45,306 --> 00:38:48,309
And a lot of them are kind of funny and will make you laugh.

661
00:38:48,309 --> 00:38:50,131
And that's really important to the idea

662
00:38:50,131 --> 00:38:51,853
because you can't just block.

663
00:38:53,388 --> 00:38:58,571
I think, and what Brian says, is when you react to something

664
00:38:58,571 --> 00:39:02,154
with a laugh, it kind of means that there's

665
00:39:02,154 --> 00:39:05,096
some truth to it that you probably hadn't considered.

666
00:39:05,096 --> 00:39:07,297
It's a subversion of expectations.

667
00:39:07,297 --> 00:39:10,379
And so I think these are really useful literally,

668
00:39:10,379 --> 00:39:14,922
but also just in the sense of creating a constraint that you

669
00:39:14,922 --> 00:39:16,883
maybe didn't have control over will help

670
00:39:16,883 --> 00:39:19,565
you become way more creative.

671
00:39:19,565 --> 00:39:20,826
So this is my current game.

672
00:39:20,826 --> 00:39:21,406
It's called Kachina.

673
00:39:23,054 --> 00:39:25,935
You control this hole in the ground, and you move it around,

674
00:39:25,935 --> 00:39:28,376
and stuff falls inside.

675
00:39:28,376 --> 00:39:30,677
And it gets bigger every time.

676
00:39:30,677 --> 00:39:32,957
So this came out of a game jam.

677
00:39:32,957 --> 00:39:36,799
And I think game jams are really important to game

678
00:39:36,799 --> 00:39:39,339
development, not necessarily as a way of starting a game,

679
00:39:39,339 --> 00:39:43,180
but just in terms of having a constraint for your process

680
00:39:43,180 --> 00:39:46,201
that will help you come up with brand new ideas and

681
00:39:46,201 --> 00:39:46,842
innovative solutions.

682
00:39:46,842 --> 00:39:50,563
So in the case of a game jam, your artistic constraint is

683
00:39:50,563 --> 00:39:50,923
time.

684
00:39:51,408 --> 00:39:54,951
And the time constraint led me to this art style,

685
00:39:54,951 --> 00:39:57,573
because it's so simple.

686
00:39:57,573 --> 00:39:59,314
And it's 3D, but it's all flat-shaded.

687
00:39:59,314 --> 00:39:59,934
There's no lighting.

688
00:39:59,934 --> 00:40:04,458
And then also the mechanic and focusing on one thing

689
00:40:04,458 --> 00:40:07,420
that I found interesting.

690
00:40:08,659 --> 00:40:11,220
For me, this game is interesting because you

691
00:40:11,220 --> 00:40:12,440
don't control an avatar.

692
00:40:12,440 --> 00:40:15,221
You control a hole, which is negative space.

693
00:40:15,221 --> 00:40:17,882
And the entire game is physics driven.

694
00:40:17,882 --> 00:40:21,104
So all these objects are physically simulated,

695
00:40:21,104 --> 00:40:25,125
and the characters have their own very simple, rudimentary AI.

696
00:40:25,125 --> 00:40:28,807
And all you're doing is just playing with that system.

697
00:40:28,807 --> 00:40:30,587
And there's a couple puzzles, but a lot of it

698
00:40:30,587 --> 00:40:34,469
is just seeing what happens when you remove things from a scene

699
00:40:34,469 --> 00:40:36,550
and when you add them back and if they change or not.

700
00:40:37,139 --> 00:40:43,722
And so the whole, so Brian Eno started in like pop music,

701
00:40:43,722 --> 00:40:46,663
and then he started to do ambient music

702
00:40:46,663 --> 00:40:47,964
and removed his own voice.

703
00:40:47,964 --> 00:40:49,484
And he thought removing his voice

704
00:40:49,484 --> 00:40:51,085
was really important to the work

705
00:40:51,085 --> 00:40:54,006
because the voice is, if you put a voice in music,

706
00:40:54,006 --> 00:40:55,947
it kind of focuses all your attention on it.

707
00:40:55,947 --> 00:40:59,709
And so this is his quote about removing the voice.

708
00:40:59,709 --> 00:41:01,770
He says, if I'm not there taking them through,

709
00:41:01,770 --> 00:41:04,651
the audience, then it's an empty space for them.

710
00:41:04,651 --> 00:41:05,631
They can move into it.

711
00:41:06,552 --> 00:41:08,914
and they can go through in their own way.

712
00:41:08,914 --> 00:41:11,195
And so that's kind of a framework for me

713
00:41:11,195 --> 00:41:12,396
in terms of design.

714
00:41:12,396 --> 00:41:17,580
So in this case, I remove a lot of authorial control

715
00:41:17,580 --> 00:41:20,522
in terms of the physics simulation.

716
00:41:20,522 --> 00:41:24,224
But I also remove your avatar and any kind of thing

717
00:41:24,224 --> 00:41:28,047
to hold onto within that simulation.

718
00:41:28,047 --> 00:41:30,628
And I think it allows you to kind of be

719
00:41:30,628 --> 00:41:31,849
inside of that system.

720
00:41:33,404 --> 00:41:37,568
instantly, rather than having to rely on a lot of narrative

721
00:41:37,568 --> 00:41:41,572
immersion that I don't think is necessarily important.

722
00:41:41,572 --> 00:41:43,874
So I wanted to talk one more time about the Windows 95

723
00:41:43,874 --> 00:41:46,817
sound, how it encapsulates everything.

724
00:41:47,582 --> 00:41:52,126
So the challenge was to create this three and one-fourth

725
00:41:52,126 --> 00:41:54,127
second song.

726
00:41:54,127 --> 00:41:57,070
And so he said, this was really funny,

727
00:41:57,070 --> 00:42:00,393
because to make that piece of music that

728
00:42:00,393 --> 00:42:05,777
contained all those ideas was an incredibly silly challenge.

729
00:42:05,777 --> 00:42:08,119
But he took it up.

730
00:42:08,119 --> 00:42:14,005
So and he used these three ideas of having a guiding theory,

731
00:42:14,005 --> 00:42:15,486
having an incredibly.

732
00:42:15,912 --> 00:42:18,554
